Then bid they the youngest to shoot but he refused it, saying, I will rather loose aU, then wound that body that I so loved living Had you ever had but halfe that love in you to him that I have, you would rather have had your own bodies mangled, than to suffer his lifelesse corps thus to be used nay, you doe not onely suffer it, but you are the actors of this act of shame and speaking this, he wept.

But as for the great deal he had done, he dide not know it at the time, that his own good servant he had just come, his good wife, but this came to pass when he made an offer to his master's wife, and that his master might make some money that he had not done, and this dide become his waye into his kingdom. So that the man that the priest had put in his seat saw him, and said to him: 'I have hade some good discourse with my Master, that will have you very sorry of your Lord. I am so sorry for you; that I should have had so much trouble with you, and so much needful to me, and that I would have done much better with your good master than you have done me at this time.' He said: 'Sir, my King, have mercy on your good King. I am a good King, and a strong one.' And the man then said: 'I will not let my King go any more, my lord, for I am well-loved. I know the best knight and well-loved knights of the world, and I am sure he will be a good King. If ye shall do this to me, and to the men of England, I will have no more trouble of my life than you have done with me

Quand je relevai la tte, l'obscurit la plus complte salait faite dans votre logement, et une lueur d'espoir tra-, versa mon esprit. Point de doute vous alliez venir, vous alliez paratre. Nulle puissance humaine ne m'et contrainte  croire que vous passeriez la journe sans me voir et sans tenir la promesse que vous m'aviez faite. Vous tiez-donc en. chemin j'en tais convaincue comme d'un article de foi. En - effet, la sonnette retentit quelqu'un tait l. - Ab 1 enfin, m'criai-je, le voici Dieu soit lou ! Je courus vers la porte et ouvris. C'tait Melchior. XXVI Je ne chercherai pas, Ludovic,  vous raconter ce que j'prouvai  la vue de cet homme. Ce fut un sentiment si bizarre, si ml, si excessif qu'il me serait impossible de l'analyser. Ce qui y dominait, c'tait la colre vis--vis de vous, et vis--vis de lui de la rpugnance. Pourquoi tait-il l et non pas vous? A quel titre se prsentait-il 1 Etait-ce de votre part? Que pouvait-il avoir  me dire? A -tout. prendre, si c'tait votre messager, vous aviez eu, en le choisissant, la main singulirement malheureuse. Il faut que ma physionomie ait exprim, en partie du moins, les sentiments qui m'agitaient, ou bien que Melchior et prpar, en habile acteur, les nuances de son rle. Tou-jours est-il qu'il s'en tira  son avantage et se conduisit de manire  me dsarmer. Dans l'opinion que je m'en tais forme, cet homme devait porter en tout lieu et en toute cir-constance les airs impertinents qui lui taient habituels et dont j'avais eu tant  souffrir. Je me figurais qu'il allait le prendre sur le mme pied et se mettre  l'aise chez moi comme il s'y

This made him to grieve exceedingly be iudging that they had received the cause of their deaths by this glasse, tooke the glasse in his hand, aud uttered words to this effect Wretched Bacon, wretched in thy knowledge, in thy understanding wretched for thy art hath beene the ruine of these two gentlemen. In this grief of his, came there newes to him of the deaths of Vandermast and Fryer Bungey This did increase his griefe, and made him sorrowfull, that in three days he would not eate any thing but kept his chamber.

Encore quelques instants, et vous alliez venir chercher votre fiance impossible de vous attendre en vous voyant je serais tombe morte  vos pieds. Nous primes donc, Melchior et moi, nos dernires dis-positions. Au petit jour, et quand la porte fut ouverte, il quitta la maison. Un rendez-vous avait t fix, et je devais aller le rejoindre. Il passa sans tre aperu peut-tre le concierge tait-il son complice. Quant  moi, je restai pendant une heure encore abme dans mes regrets et mes remords. -Toutes vos bonts me revinrent alors  la mmoire, et je me trouvai bien ingrate, bien cruelle et en mme temps bien dchue. -Qu'ai liez-vous penser de moi? XXX - Pourtant, Ludovic, je vous crivis quelques mots, non pas tels que j'aurais voulu les crire, mais assez prcis pour que dsormais vous me regardassiez comme perdue pour vous. Je n'tais plus digne de le porter, quoi qu'il arrivt et de quel-que faon que tournassent les choses. Je rejoignis Melchior et le trouvai ivre de son bonheur. Par le concours des circonstances, j'tais compromise  un point qu'aucune rparation n'tait possible, si ce n'est celle que pouvait m'offrir Melchior. Son but tait atteint il m'avait mise  la discrtion de son hon-neur. Triste garantie ! et je le vis bien plus tard. Je succombai une barrire s'leva entre vous et moi je ne pouvais plus tre  vous, Ludovic. Les heures s'cou-laient il fallut prendre un parti. Encore quelques instants, et vous alliez venir chercher votre fiance impossible de vous attendre en vous voyant je serais tombe morte  vos pieds. Nous prmes donc, Melchior et moi, nos dernires dis-positions. Au petit jour, et quand la porte fut ouverte, il quitta la maison. Un rendez-vous avait t fix, et je devais aller le rejoindre. Il passa sans tre aperu peut-tre le concierge tait-il son complice. Quant  moi, je restai pendant une heure encore abme dans mes regrets et mes remords. Toutes vos bonts me revinrent alors  la mmoire, et je me trouvai bien ingrate, bien cruelle et en mme temps bien dchue. Qu'alliez-vous penser de moi ? Hlas ! quoi que vous pussiez en penser, la ralit dpasserait vos suppositions. J'tais une fille dshonore ! XXX Pourtant, Ludovic, je vous crivis quelques mots, non pas tels que j'aurais voulu les crire, mais assez prcis pour que dsormais vous me regardassiez comme perdue pour vous. Puis j'enlevai de mon doigt l'anneau qui me venait de ma grand'mre et qui avait si mal prserv mon honneur. Je n'tais plus digne de le porter, quoi qu'il arrivt et de quel-que faon que tournassent les choses. Je rejoignis Melchior et le trouvai ivre de son bonheur. Moi-mme,  ce premier moment, j'prouvai ce vertige des sens qui n'est que la fausse monnaie de l'amour. Melchior

Being one day in his study in this manner, and asleepe, the Walloon souldier was got in to him, and had drawne his sword to kiU him but as hee was ready for to strike, downe fell the ball out of Fryer Bacon's hand, and waked him. Hee seeing the souldier stand there with a sworddrawne, asked him what hee was? and wherefore hee came there in that manner? The souldier boldly answered him thus I am a WaUoon, and a souldier, and more then this, a villaine I am come hither, because I was sent I was sent, because I was hyred I was hyred, because I durst do it the thing I should doe, is not done the thing to be done, is to kdl thee thus have you heard what I am and why I came. Hee boldly told him, Vandermast the Germane coniurer Fryer Bacon then asked him what religion he was of? He answered, of" the German, that was in his owne church. ocr.region: LES TLPHONISTES DANS LA BATAILLE 9 III LA FERME DE BEAUSJOUR L A feuille  la main, le sergent, debout devant l'abri du colonel, faisait la rpartition des postes. - Duruy, dit-il, tu vas monter avec tes hommes au secteur I, tu longeras un peu la route jusqu'aux boyaux B 1 et B 2, au tournant du ruisseau, ils sont perpendiculaires  la Grande Transversale, aprs quoi tu monteras tout droit jus-qu'au poste du commandant. Ne t'amuse pas en chemin, car  peu prs cinq cents mtres avant d'arriver, il voltige des bom-bes!. Legrand, tu prends le secteur H, dangereux pour les marmites, surtout au Bois Equerre tu suivras le boyau central jusqu'au boyau Boscary, o tu trouveras le poste de son com-mandant. Attention vous autres, baissez la tte, les balles tra-versent la route! Je garde deux hommes avec moi au poste du colonel,  da borne 16. La nuit tait venne, pas de lune, une obscurit complte rgnait sur les tranches, et sauf les coups de fusils espacs, partant des premires lignes, la soire tait calme. Les fuses dans le ciel irradiaient par moments l'horizon de leur courbe gracieuse, inondant les parapets d'une lueur blafarde. L'quipe se spara en deux. Puis,  la file, les nouveaux venus longrent la route le plus prs possible du remblai pour viter les balles perdues qui froufroutaient avec un bruit de soie, allant frapper les troncs d'arbres de l'autre ct du ruis-seau. - Pour une belle nuit, c'est une beMe nuit, remarqua R-gnier, un combat de ngres sous un tunnel et  chaque fuse il gouaillait Ah! la belle bleue! - Allez, activez le mouvement, lana Legrand impatient, en laissant derrire lui Duruy qui entrait dans son boyau, nous avons encore un bout de chemin! Sans se dtourner il poursuivit sa marche  ttons, cher-chant  ehaque trou la pancarte indicatrice.

ocr.sentence: CE PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE.
ocr.region: CE qu'on PEUT VOIR DANS UNE rue. 257, j'obis, tant il y avait en moi de confusion et de trouble. Il faut si. peu de chose pour arrter une confidence sur les lvres, surtout lorsqu'il s'agit de s'accuser d'un tort et de se mettre  la merci d'autrui ! On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, -on puise des mo-tifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant- de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul mais une force imprieuse et presque indpen-dante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers ? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, .comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon coeur Peut-tre, hlas ! en interrogeant mieux ce coeur, aurais-je trouv le dernier mot de ces rticences. La suite ne l'a que trop prouv j'tais dj touche, j'entrais dans cette srie de faiblesses qui m'ont perdue. C'est ici que j'ai besoin de votre pardon, Ludovic, d'un pardon absolu et gnreux. Point d'excuse possible, rien qui puisse pallier ce commen-cement de trahison. Vous aviez t pour moi le meilleur, le plus dvou et le plus fidle des amis vous n'aviez qu'une pense, mon bonheur qu'un but, notre union. Jamais, c'est une justice que je me plais  vous rendre, aucun chagrin ne m'est venu de vous si j'exprimais un dsir, vous vous em-pressiez de le satisfaire si j'avais un ennui, vous vous offriez - le partager. Vous tiez de ces loyaux compagnons qu'une femme est trop heureuse de rencontrer dans sa vie, qui l'as-sistent dans les bons et les mauvais jours et se donnent sans rserve comme sans calcul. Je voyais tout cela, je le sentais et ne mconnaissais point-vos mrites. Lui, au contraire, qu'tait-il et quel fonds pouvais-je -

Nay, said Fryer Bacon, I pray gentlemen at my request tarry a little, and heare some of my mans musicke you are byred reasonable well already, I hope in courtesie you will not deny mee so small a request. That will wee not, said they all. Miles thought now to have some sport with them, which hee had, and therefore plaid lustily on his tabor and pipe so soone as they heard him play against their wills they fell a dauncing, and that after such a laborious manner, that they quickly wearied themselves for they had all that while the bagges of money in their hands. Yet had Fryer Bacon not revenge enough of them, but bid his man Miles leave them some larger measure as hee thought fitting, which Miles did. Miles straight ledde them out of the house into the fields, they followed him, dauncing after a wilde anticke man-ner then led hee them over a broad dike full of water, and they followed him still, but not so good a way as he went for he went over the bridge, but they by reason of their dauncing, could not keepe the bridge, but fell off, and dauncing through the water then led hee them through a way where a horse might very well have been up to the belly they followed him, and were so durtie, as though they had wallowed in the myre like swine sometime gave hee them rest onely to laugh at them then were they so sleepie when hee did not play, that they fell to the ground. Then on a sudden would hee play againe, and make them start up and follow him. Thus kept hee them the better part of the night. At

ocr.sentence: he said to Rush, thou lewd fellow, what hast thou done to this waggon that I am thus arayed therein ?
ocr.region: 277 OF FRIER RUSH. then he said to Rush, thou lew d fellow, what bast thou done to this waggon that I am thus arayed therein ? Rush answered and said sir, I have done nothing but as you commanded me. That is not, said the Priour, for I commaunded thee to take greace and grease but the wheeles and the axeltrees, and thou hast taken tarre and annointed it all over, both within and without. Why hast thou done so ? Sir said Rush, I understoode you bad me doe so. And when the Priour sawe there was no other remedie, he commanded his servants to makeready another waggon, and in the meane season, the Priour went into his chamber, and put on another babite, and came againe and mounted into the waggon and went their way, and so long they rode, that they came to their iourneyes end. And when they were alighted at their lodging, the Priour caUed for his supper, and anon every thing was made ready, and the good man of the house and the Priour sate downe to supper together, and made good cheere and then the Priour called for wine of the best, and anon he had his commandement. And when the good man of the house and the Priour had supped, Rush and bis fellowes sate downe to the rever sions that their maisters bad left, but they had no wine wherefore Rush was very sad, and ever he mused by what policie he might get some wine. And anon he called the wife of the house and said Mistresse, I pray you fill a pottle of wine for me and my fellowes, and so shee did and when that was gone, they caUed for another and then they called for the third, and so ended their

ocr.region: 274 A PLEASANT HISTORIE had been there should have seene good buffets given on both parties. And when Frier Rush saw that they were fighting together, anon he blew out all the candles and lamps that were burning in the church, and left no manner of Hght therein whereby the one might see the other and when he had so done, be tooke his truncheon in his hand, and went into the Quier among the thickest of the Friers the which were fighting freshly without light, and there he laid so lustily about, that many of them he felled to the ground, and left them there for dead, and when he had so done, he stole his way from them, and as hee went, he found standing in the portaU of the Quier, a great olde deske, and anon hee tooke the deske betweene both his hands, and threw it over the portad into the Quier among aU the Friers, and hurt many sore, in so much that some had an arme broken, and some a legge, and other some had their noses, cleane pared from their faces, that the bloud ranne in their mouthes, and as for broken heads to the hard scalpe were no dainty, for every man had one, there scaped none free away, who had been there, should have had a goodly pastime to see the Friers creepe about the Quier, and in steede of Domine labia they cried out alas and well away. Then when the fray was done, and all the noyse seased, Rush came in among them with a candell light in his hand, and made as he had knowne nothing thereof, and said to them Fie for shame sirs, how fortuned this discord to faU among your selves ? I see well now you regard not your honour, nor the good

" That they had so been a long time together," answered the people. " He, as I, have been much vexed wherfore by this thing which I have said, because, in all their many disputes, they have kept themselves very long and so good, which is all that is best for a young man, and for a man of good morals," replied hee. " So, I ask, what is that?"  and they asked why it was not sooner to the man from whom it happened, when he was there, when he had received the good things which he had donee of this kind? " He answered that he has been much vexed wherfore with this thing which he has said, because he hath not much time, and because of that hee has gone forth againe, and after that, and hath not any day's rest, that any man of a well to doe will have, when he has so many disputes to fight upon, as there is no rest for the young man to be well with men to doe ; but it befell him that hee hath much trouble for this matter, because it shall be worse for him if it is a battle for himself, and he must knowe that some young man of good morals hath a good thing to doe, and they have more reason to complain of him than if they were of his own free choice. ocr.sentence: ANOTHER time it fortuned that the Priour had a journey to ride into the country about a little businesse that hee had there to doe, and anon he called Rush his servant unto him and said, Rush goe thy way into the court, and take with thee a dish full of greace, and greace well the wheeles and axeltrees of the waggon, and make all things ready against to-morrow in the morning, for I must ride forth to-morrow betimes, then Rush departed from his maister, and went about his businesse, and insteed of greace, hee tooke a great vessell full of tarre, and anointed the waggon all over with it, both within and without, and especially in the place where the Priour should sit and when he had done, he returned to his maister's chamber, then the Priour demanded of Rush, if he had done as he commanded him yea sir said Rush, ye may ride when please you, and so they went to their beds.

ocr.sentence: their malicious mindes and angry hearts, every man after other went privately to Frier Rush to lend them staves, in so much that there was not a Frier in the place but he had one, and they never went without their staves under their habite, and the one knew not that the other had any, they kept them so secretly.
ocr.region: OF FRIER RUSH. 273 filling their malicious mindes and angry hearts, every man after other went privately to Frier Rush to lend them staves, in so much that there was not a Frier in the place but he had one, and they never went without their staves under their habite, and the one knew not that the other had any, they kept them so secretly. And when Frier Rush had delivered aH his staves, he was right glad in his heart, for he knew right well there should be a great fray among them, either one time or other. So it fortuned afterward, as it is a common cus-tome among religious people at an high feast, to keepe solemne service, and every man to be at Mattens at midnight, and so upon a good night, all the whole Covent assembled together in the Quier, and were ready to begin Mattens, they taried for nothing but for the comming of the Priour. Then anon the Priour came into the Quier, and sate him downe in his place, and as he looked about him, he espied that the Subpriour was there present, and with that his heart began to grudge of the olde anger that was fallen betweene them two, and he thought in his minde that he could never be revenged in a better time, and sodainly he rose out of his place, and went to the Subpriour, and with his fist he gave him a good buffet, and the Subpriour which was moved with the stroke, started unto the Priour and gave him another buffet, and with that they went freshly together by the eares, and when the other Friers saw that, every man rose out of their places, and drew out their Truncheons, and together they went who VOL. I.
